      "type": "Term",
      "front": "utopian communities",
      "back": "Most utopian communities also tried to find substitutes for conventional gender relations and marriage patterns. To outside observers, utopian communities like Oneida seemed a case of \"voluntary slavery.\" But because of their members' selfless devotion to the teachings and rules laid down by their leader, spiritually oriented communities often achieved remarkable longevity. Briefly explain how utopian communities challenged existing ideas about property and marriage.",
