      "type": "Term",
      "front": "common school",
      "back": "Antislavery leaders took advantage of the rapid development of print technology and the expansion of literacy due to common school education to spread their message. The largest effort at institution building before the Civil War came in the movement to establish common schools —that is, tax-supported state school systems open to all children. The common school movement created the first real career opportunity for women, who quickly came to dominate the ranks of teachers.",
