      "back": "Even before the appearance of The Liberator, as we have seen, northern free blacks had organized in opposition to the Colonization Society. Before the 1830s, those white Americans willing to contemplate an end to bondage almost always coupled calls for abolition with the \"colonization\" of freed slaves—their deportation to Africa, the Caribbean, or Central America. In 1816, proponents of this idea founded the American Colonization Society, which promoted the gradual abolition of slavery and the settlement of black Americans in Africa.",
      "hint": "Even before the appearance of The Liberator, as we have seen, northern free blacks had organized in opposition to the Colonization Society.",
