      "id": "chapter12-fc-029",
      "chapterId": "chapter12",
      "type": "Term",
      "front": "Spreading the Abolitionist Message",
      "back": "By portraying slaves as sympathetic men and women, and as Christians at the mercy of slaveholders who split up families and set bloodhounds on innocent mothers and children, Stowe's melodrama gave the abolitionist message a powerful human appeal. A brilliant orator, Weld trained a band of speakers who brought the abolitionist message into the heart of the rural and small-town North.",
