      "id": "chapter12-fc-038",
      "chapterId": "chapter12",
      "type": "Person",
      "front": "William Lloyd Garrison",
      "back": "Militant abolitionist editor. In 1835, a Boston crowd led William Lloyd Garrison through the streets with a rope around his neck. Not until the appearance in 1831 of The Liberator, William Lloyd Garrison's weekly journal published in Boston, did the new breed of abolitionism find a permanent voice. As late as 1834, northern blacks, attracted by Garrison's rejection of colonization and his demand for equal rights for black Americans, made up a majority of the journal's subscribers.",
